INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6bbb793e-8872-47c3-82fa-de7ac335988e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$wandb Model Registry to REST API — Artifact Aliases, Latency Logging, and SLA Alerts$escape$,
  $escape$Deploying a model registered in W&B's Model Registry as a REST endpoint ties your serving layer directly to an artifact alias — `production`, `staging`, or a semantic version tag. At server startup, pull the artifact with `wandb.Api().artifact("entity/project/model:production")` and call `.download()` to materialize weights locally. Pair this with a single long-lived `wandb.init(job_type="serving", resume="allow")` run to stream per-request metrics without the overhead of spawning a new run per call.

For batching, accumulate requests over a configurable window (e.g., 20 ms) before calling `model.predict()`, then log batch size alongside latency: `run.log({"latency_ms": ..., "batch_size": ...})`. SLA enforcement is built into W&B via `run.alert()` — fire a Slack or email notification directly from your serving process when p99 crosses a threshold using `wandb.AlertLevel.WARN`. Crucially, pinning the artifact alias in your deployment config means promoting a new model to production is a single Registry update — no redeployment required if you resolve the alias at startup.$escape$,
  $escape$import wandb, time
from fastapi import FastAPI

app = FastAPI()
api = wandb.Api()
artifact = api.artifact("myorg/myproject/classifier:production")
model = load_model(artifact.download())  # your loader
run = wandb.init(project="myproject", job_type="serving", resume="allow")

@app.post("/predict")
async def predict(payload: dict):
    t0 = time.perf_counter()
    result = model.predict([payload["input"]])[0]
    latency_ms = (time.perf_counter() - t0) * 1000
    run.log({"latency_ms": latency_ms})
    if latency_ms > 80:
        run.alert("SLA breach", text=f"{latency_ms:.1f}ms > 80ms p99", level=wandb.AlertLevel.WARN)
    return {"prediction": result}$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
